[6/20/96 public]

The current synopsis for this command is:

   clock set [dts_entity]
      {-to DTS_timestamp [-abruptly -epoch epoch_number] [-bypass] |
       -epoch epoch_number}

When '-to' is used, the '-abruptly' and '-epoch' options must be used
together, or not at all:

      dcecp> clock set -to [clock show]
      dcecp>

      dcecp> clock set -to [clock show] -abruptly -epoch 0
      dcecp>

      dcecp> clock set -to [clock show] -abruptly
      Error: '-epoch' option not specified.
      dcecp>

      dcecp> clock set -to [clock show] -epoch 1
      Error: '-abruptly' option not specified.
      dcecp>

So the '-abruptly' and '-epoch' options should not be separated.

However, the syntax above implies that '-bypass' can be used standalone,
or in combination with '-abruptly' and '-epoch' (when '-to' is specified).
This is NOT the case:

      dcecp> clock set -to [clock show] -bypass
      dcecp>

      dcecp> clock set -to [clock show] -bypass -abrutply -epoch 1
      Error: When using '-bypass', other options are not allowed.
      dcecp>

As you can see, it can be used alone, but not in combination.  This
makes the synopsis incorrect as described, but not for the reasons
listed below.  Change this line of the synopsis from:

      {-to DTS_timestamp [-abruptly -epoch epoch_number] [-bypass] |

to

      {-to DTS_timestamp [-abruptly -epoch epoch_number | -bypass] |

which means you can use '-to' alone, or you can use '-to' with
the '-abruptly/-epoch' combination, or you '-to' with '-bypass'.
But '-bypass' cannot be used with the other options.

This change should be applied to both places in the dcecp_clock manpage.

[6/19/96 public]
Status changed to cancel. According to developers here, the 
current syntax for the -abruptly and -epoch options is correct 
as it stands.

