Firstly, the server(8dce) man page, in the ATTRIBUTES section under "services",
says 

            bindings protocol_sequence_list
                      A list of string bindings identifying the service.
                      This is only specified for well-known endpoints.

However, the restriction that it is only specified for well-known endpoints
is not enforced.  Examples in the "server create" subpage list bindings without
endpoints, and there is no way I know of for dced to check the IDL definition
of an interface for well-known endpoints.  I think that the sentence
"This is only specified for well-known endpoints." should be removed.

Secondly, under the subpage "server stop" of the server(8dce) man page, the
reader should be warned that if there is more than one instance of a server
using a given interface, object UUID and a given binding without endpoints, then
the "rpc" method of stopping the server will stop a randomly-selected instance
of the server -- NOT NECESSARILY THE INSTANCE SPECIFIED IN THE COMMAND.  This is
due to the inability of the RPC runtime to distinguish server instances on any
criteria other than interface and object or endpoint, and the fact that the RPC
specification allows multiple server instances to share the same interface and
object UUID.  This problem does not exist with the other methods of stopping a
server, which will stop only the instance specified in the command.  If the
"rpc" method must be used, then this problem can be avoided by starting only one
server instance for any server config object, and assigning a unique object UUID
for each server config object.

