[8/8/94 public]

	dcecp's "user create" command creates a user and creates a CDS
directory for the user. It then sets the acl for the directory. Supposedly,
the user should now be able to create entries under this directory.

	The problem is, the user will be able to create objects under the
directory, but not directories, since he needs write permission to the
clearinghouse to be able to create directories.

	It is not as simple as adding an acl to grant user xxx the permision
to the clearinghouse. Imagine hundreds of users in a cell, you should not have
the acl for the clearinghouse to list all the users. It has to be group.

[8/8/94 public]
I've changed this to a doc bug.  Ward please include something to the
following effect in the section on customizing (or maybe using) the user
create command.

As we ship DCE 1.1 the user create command will set the ACL on the
/.:/users/<username> directory so that users can insert things.  This alone
lets them insert objects and links.  To insert directories (a much more
expensive proposition) you also need write access to the clearinghouse that
will hold the directory.  The user create script does NOT change this
because: 

 * We don't know what the name of the clearinghouse is, though it could
   default to the clearinghouse holding /.:/users/<username>
 * If every user is going to have write access to the clearinghouse, why
   not just put {any_other rw-t-} on the clearinghouse.  FYI the default
   is: 
	dcecp> acl show /.:/absolut_ch
	{unauthenticated r--t-}
	{group subsys/dce/cds-admin rwdtc}
	{group subsys/dce/cds-server rwdtc}
	{any_other r--t-}
 * Directories are expensive and perhaps the admin does not want users
   creating them.

Any of the above could be changed by admin policy and the user create
script modified to allow for that policy.  The section on customizing
should mention this.  The section on *using* this command should have a big
bold note describing that in the *default* config users will not be able to
add directories.

